### Feature 4: Federation Rule Validation & Error Categories

**As a developer**, I want malformed or unsupported federation usage to fail fast with a clear, categorized reason, so misconfiguration surfaces up front instead of producing a broken schema.

**Expected Behavior / Usage:**

The input request carries an operation selector of `service_sdl` and an `sdl` string, exactly as in Feature 1, but the SDL violates a federation composition rule. Instead of a schema, the transformer emits a single neutral error line of the form `error=<category>`, where the category names the rule that was broken. The distinct categories are: `unsupported_federation_version` (the schema imports the federation specification at a version the transformer does not support); `multiple_federation_links` (the schema declares the federation import link more than once, whether via repeated schema annotations or via a mix of schema definition and extension); `unsupported_link_import` (the schema imports a feature from a specification version older than the one in which that feature was introduced); `unsupported_rename` (the schema attempts to rename a directive that is not allowed to be renamed); `missing_key` (an object implementing a federated interface fails to declare the key fields that interface requires); `schema_problem` (the schema cannot be constructed because of a structural problem); and `invalid_schema` (the constructed schema fails federation validation). For schemas whose entity resolution involves an abstract (interface or union) type, the request may also carry an `abstractTypeResolvers` array naming those abstract types so the transformation can proceed far enough to reach the relevant validation.

